om","Hen, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Weston, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Weston,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of numerous places called Weston, from Old English <i>west</i> ‘west’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte west tun(e)</i> ‘at the west farmstead, settlement’ (Old English <i>west</i> + <i>tūn</i>), or from Middle English <i>(bi) weste(n)tune</i> (Old English <i>be westan tūne</i> or <i>be west in tūne</i>), denoting someone who lived either to the west of a settlement or in the western part of a settlement. The latter was a common surname in Sussex."],"variants":[{"name":"Wesson","meanings":["English (Midlands and Kent): variant of   Weston  .","History: John Wesson came from England to Salem, MA, in 1644."]}]},{"name":"Magister","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Manningtree (Essex), recorded as  <i>Manystre</i> in 1291 and 1343, which reportedly had the local pronunciations  <i>Manister</i> and  <i>Manisty</i>.","2  English: locative name perhaps from Manesty in Borrowdale (Cumb), which is recorded as  <i>Manistie</i>,  <i>Maynister</i> in 1564."],"variants":[{"name":"Manistre","meanings":["English:  see  Manister  ."]},{"name":"Manisty","meanings":["English:  see  Manister  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":46,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":55,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John De Weston, Magister was born in 1169, in Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England, his father, Hamon de Weston, was 33 and his mother, Maud of Surrey, was 19. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Isolde de Newton. He died on 3 November 1227, in Staffordshire, England, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1169–3 November 1227":"1169–3. november 1227","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1174–1234":"1174–1234","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1197–Ma